issue.title: Quine session
issue.body:
### Abstract

Quines (programs that output themselves) are a great example of metaprogramming and self-references, and when written in a non trivial way, could seem like black programming magic. This hands-on session will nullify the magic by reviewing the process of a complex quine creation, step by step.

### Technologies

JavaScript / Node

```js
(f=_=>console.log(`(f=${f})()`))()
```

issue.title: gpg volume encryption
issue.body:
### Abstract

A gpg-based encrypted volume mount-unmount utility.

### Technologies

* GPG
* Node

### Why yes

To replace [tcmount](https://github.com/danyshaanan/tcmount) which is based on TrueCrypt.

### Why not

Cause full disk encryption will be better.

### Links

* https://patrick.uiterwijk.org/blog/2013/2/25/gpg-encrypted-loopback-disks
* https://www.npmjs.com/package/openpgp
* https://www.gnupg.org/

issue.title: Big file git-like repo
issue.body:
### Abstract

Handling directories with very big, mostly unchanging files (think downloaded video files) in git has a few harsh consequences - Git keeps data of deleted files, and keeps duplicate copies of existing files. (in the working directory, and as git objects).

To solve both problems, git can be used to track only a representation of the directory structure:

```
589cd8fb67ae7cfb01a550161e90e753a82db696 somedir/a.file
d626ba69caac9b13748961671112406b1fa44bf7 someDir/another.file
ea1032162e0d43161f56b8e2a20133465df2ab1c someDir/x.file
```

and a top level command can abstract git commands and apply such representations on the working directory by moving/renaming files, identified by their SHA sums.

### Technologies

* Git

### Why yes

This seems to me like very interesting development, specifically in terms of UX, and the abstraction of git commands and their meanings.

### Why not

The goal might be more easily achieved by hard-linking files to their SHA sums in a specific directory, which can then be rsynced safely between machines, along with a record of the true location of each SHA-sum file. A 'save' command should create the SHA links and the record, and on the target machine, an 'apply' command could read the record and hard-link the SHA files to their original location. (and preform a cleanup).

issue.title: Electron image viewer
issue.body:
### Abstract

An Electron image viewer, to traverse directories and view/delete/move/rename/edit image files.

### Technologies

* Electron
* `fs` or similar
* React probably

### Why yes

Cause I haven't found any OSX image viewer that is as simple and productive as IrfanView.

### Why not

This doesn't seem to be too fun to develop.

### Links

* [Electron](http://electron.atom.io/)
* [Electron app init](https://github.com/oct82/electron-init)
